                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-184-off1072 t18320517-184-crimeloc1075"></join>; the prisoner's wife has worked for me for four or five years - the prisoner is a <rs id="t18320517-184-deflabel1076" type="occupation">servant out of place</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-184-defend1497 t18320517-184-deflabel1076"></join>. I placed a pair of shoes on a board<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183205170096"></xptr>on the 3rd of May; the prisoner came to my shop about twelve o'clock - I left him, and went down stairs; when I came up, my wife had sent him out; I missed the shoes, and when he came back I spoke to him - he said, "You can't suspect me - I have no property about me;" the officer then came, searched him, and found the shoes in his coat pocket - I had missed some before.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by Mr. LEE. Q.Was there any mark on these shoes? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>JOHN CRIDDLE (Police-constable H 142). I was sent for, and took the prisoner. I found these shoes in his pocket, and this duplicate of another pair in his fob.</p>
               <p>SAMUEL STEVENS. I am a pawnbroker. I have two pairs of shoes, pawned with me - I do not know by whom, but I gave this duplicate for them.</p>
               <p>MR. SNELL. These are all mine.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Had the prisoner's wife been there that day? A.No, not for some years - the prisoner always brought the work home.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received an excellent character,</p>
